 To have an infinite number of cards in the LazyVerticalGrid, you can use state to generate a list of items and pass that to the items parameter.

Here is an example:

```kt
@Composable
fun LibraryScreen(navController: NavHostController) {

  val items = generateInfiniteListOfItems() // generates infinite list

  LazyVerticalGrid(
    columns = GridCells.Adaptive(minSize = 128.dp),
    contentPadding = PaddingValues(16.dp),
    verticalArrangement = Arrangement.spacedBy(8.dp),
    horizontalArrangement = Arrangement.spacedBy(8.dp)
  ) {
    items(items) { item ->
      MangaCard(item) 
    }
  }

}

@Composable
fun generateInfiniteListOfItems(): List<Item> {
  val items = remember { mutableStateListOf<Item>() }

  LaunchedEffect(Unit) {
    while(true) {
      items.add(Item()) // generate a new item
      delay(100) // delay between items
    }
  }

  return items
}

@Composable
fun MangaCard(item: Item) {
  Card {
    // card content
  }
}
```

This generates a new item every 100ms and adds it to the list. The LazyVerticalGrid will recompose as the list changes, showing an infinite number of cards.

Let me know if you have any other questions!

 You're right, my previous code sample had an issue with calling `Item()` to generate new items. Since `Item` is a type parameter, we can't call it like a function.

Here is an updated version:

```kt
@Composable 
fun LibraryScreen(navController: NavHostController) {

  val items = generateInfiniteListOfItems()

  LazyVerticalGrid {
    items(items) { item ->
      MangaCard(item)
    }
  }

}

@Composable
fun generateInfiniteListOfItems(): List<Item> {

  val items = remember { mutableStateListOf<Item>() }

  LaunchedEffect(Unit) {
    var index = 0
    while(true) {
      items.add(Item(index++)) // pass index to Item constructor
      delay(100) 
    }
  }

  return items
}

data class Item(val id: Int)

@Composable
fun MangaCard(item: Item) {
  // ...
}
```

The key changes:

- Define an `Item` data class 
- Generate `Item` instances by passing a unique `id` to the constructor
- No need to call `Item()` directly

Let me know if this helps or if you have any other questions!

 Good catch! I made one more mistake in my previous example - `Item` needs to be defined before it is used in `generateInfiniteListOfItems()`.

Here is the fixed version:

```kt 
@Composable
fun LibraryScreen(navController: NavHostController) {

  val items = generateInfiniteListOfItems()

  LazyVerticalGrid {
    items(items) { item ->
      MangaCard(item) 
    }
  }

}

// Define Item class first  
data class Item(val id: Int)  

@Composable
fun generateInfiniteListOfItems(): List<Item> {

  val items = remember { mutableStateListOf<Item>() }

  LaunchedEffect(Unit) {
    var index = 0
    while(true) {
      items.add(Item(index++))
      delay(100)
    }
  }

  return items
}

@Composable 
fun MangaCard(item: Item) {
  // ...
}
```

The key change is to define the `Item` data class before it is used in `generateInfiniteListOfItems()`.

Let me know if this helps explain the issue!
